{{refimprove|date=June 2017}}
The '''Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grant''', more commonly known by its acronym '''SEOG''', is a [[federal assistance]] grant reserved for college students with the greatest need for [[Student financial aid (United States)|financial aid]] to attend school. To be eligible for this grant applicants must meet all of the following criteria<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fseog.com/|title=Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grant (FSEOG)|website=FSEOG (Grants) Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grant|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>:
#To be a [[United States citizen]] or eligible non-citizen, #To not have a [[bachelor's degree]], #To not be in [[default (finance)|default]] of any federal student loan, #To not have a [[Federal Pell Grant]] overpayment, #To file their [[FAFSA]].
The maximum FSEOG is $4,000 a year and the amount applicants are eligible for is at the discretion of the college. To obtain the FSEOG, the student must accomplish and submit the Free Application for Federal Student Aid or FAFSA<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.salliemae.com/college-planning/financial-aid/understand-college-grants/federal-supplemental-education-opportunity-grant/|title=FSEOG - Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grant|work=Sallie Mae|access-date=2018-08-02|language=en-US}}</ref>.
