]] from the [[Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation]] in 2011. He is known for, along with his colleague [[Linda Gottfredson]], helping to expose a controversial Residence Life Program at the University of Delaware in 2007. After critics described the program as "appalling" and an attempt at indoctrination, the program was quickly shut down by the University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.org/articles/NAS_Delaware_Head_Jan_Blits_Keynotes_Tomorrow_at_FIRE_Conference|title=NAS Delaware Head Jan Blits Keynotes Tomorrow at FIRE Conference |website=National Association of Scholars|date=2011-07-15|access-date=2017-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nas.org/articles/NAS_Delaware_Affiliate_President_Jan_Blits_Receives_Academic_Freedom_Award|title=NAS Delaware Affiliate President Jan Blits Receives Academic Freedom Award |website=National Association of Scholars|access-date=2017-10-21}}</ref> Blits also fought alongside Gottfredson against the University's attempts to ban them from receiving research funding from the [[Pioneer Fund]] in the early 1990s. Ultimately, they were successful in their attempts to be allowed to accept such funds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/12397/title/U--Delaware-Reaches-Accord-On-Race-Studies/|date=1992-07-06|title=U. Delaware Reaches Accord On Race Studies|website=The Scientist|access-date=2017-10-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.city-journal.org/html/real-war-science-14782.html|title=The Real War on Science|date=2016-10-14|work=City Journal|author=Tierney, John|access-date=2017-10-21|language=en}}</ref>
