{{use British English|date=August 2017}}
{{use DMY dates|date=August 2017}}
The '''Royal Air Force Educational Service''' was a civilian-manned service within the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Royal Air Force]] which provided instruction for [[aircraft apprentice]]s and airmen, mainly in engineering, but also in other subjects.

The service was established shortly after the formation of the Royal Air Force in 1918. Preference for recruitment as Civilian Education Officers was given to men who had served as [[commissioned officer]]s in the armed forces during the [[First World War]]<ref>"Public Appointments", ''[[The Times]]'', 31 December 1927</ref> until 1930, when it was extended to all ex-servicemen.<ref>"Public Appointments", ''[[The Times]]'', 9 January 1930</ref> From 1937 advertisements no longer stated that ex-servicemen would be given preference.<ref>"Public Appointments", ''[[The Times]]'', 8 January 1937</ref> From 1930 a [[academic degree|degree]] was required.<ref>"Public Appointments", ''[[The Times]]'', 9 January 1930</ref>

On 1 October 1946, the Educational Service was disbanded and replaced by the commissioned officers of the new RAF Education Branch.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1946/1946%20-%202058.html ''Flight'', 10 October 1946]</ref> Many Education Officers had already been commissioned during the [[Second World War]].

